export default "# AWS EC2 Deployment Setup Guide\n\n## Overview\n\nThis document summarizes a general-purpose production deployment setup using AWS EC2 for hosting web applications.\n\n---\n\n# Architecture\n\n```text\nInternet\n   ↓\nCloudflare / Domain DNS\n   ↓\nAWS EC2 Instance\n   ├── Nginx\n   ├── Python Backend (Flask/FastAPI/Django)\n   ├── Gunicorn/Uvicorn\n   ├── Frontend Static Files\n   ├── Redis\n   └── systemd Services\n```\n\n---\n\n# 1. Create AWS EC2 Instance\n\nNavigate to:\n\n```text\nAWS Console → EC2 → Launch Instance\n```\n\n## Recommended Configuration\n\n| Setting        | Recommended Value       |\n| -------------- | ----------------------- |\n| OS             | Ubuntu Server 24.04 LTS |\n| Instance Type  | t3.small or t3.medium   |\n| Storage        | 20–30 GB gp3 SSD        |\n| Authentication | SSH Key Pair            |\n\n---\n\n# 2. Configure Security Group\n\nAllow inbound traffic for:\n\n| Port | Purpose |\n| ---- | ------- |\n| 22   | SSH     |\n| 80   | HTTP    |\n| 443  | HTTPS   |\n\nDo not expose internal application ports publicly.\n\n---\n\n# 3. Allocate Elastic IP\n\nNavigate to:\n\n```text\nEC2 → Elastic IPs\n```\n\nAllocate and associate an Elastic IP with the instance.\n\nBenefits:\n\n* Permanent public IP\n* Stable SSH access\n* Stable domain mapping\n* Stable API endpoints\n\n---\n\n# 4. Connect to the Server\n\nExample SSH command:\n\n```bash\nssh -i ~/Downloads/my-key.pem ubuntu@YOUR_ELASTIC_IP\n```\n\nSecure the key first:\n\n```bash\nchmod 400 ~/Downloads/my-key.pem\n```\n\n---\n\n# 5. Update the Server\n\n```bash\nsudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y\n```\n\nReboot if kernel updates were installed:\n\n```bash\nsudo reboot\n```\n\n---\n\n# 6. Install Core Packages\n\n```bash\nsudo apt install -y \\\n    git \\\n    nginx \\\n    redis-server \\\n    python3-pip \\\n    python3-venv \\\n    nodejs \\\n    npm\n```\n\n---\n\n# 7. Install Python 3.14 (Optional)\n\nUbuntu ships with a system Python version.\n\nTo install Python 3.14 separately:\n\n```bash\nsudo apt install -y software-properties-common\nsudo add-apt-repository ppa:deadsnakes/ppa\nsudo apt update\n\nsudo apt install -y \\\n    python3.14 \\\n    python3.14-venv \\\n    python3.14-dev\n```\n\nVerify:\n\n```bash\npython3.14 --version\n```\n\nDo not replace the system Python globally.\n\n---\n\n# 8. Clone Application Repository\n\n```bash\nmkdir -p ~/apps\ncd ~/apps\n\ngit clone YOUR_REPOSITORY_URL\n```\n\n---\n\n# 9. Create Python Virtual Environment\n\n```bash\ncd YOUR_PROJECT\n\npython3.14 -m venv venv\nsource venv/bin/activate\n```\n\nInstall dependencies:\n\n```bash\npip install -r requirements.txt\n```\n\n---\n\n# 10. Configure Environment Variables\n\nCreate a local environment file:\n\n```text\n.env\n```\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nOPEN_API_KEY=...\nREDIS_URL=redis://localhost:6379\n```\n\n---\n\n# 11. Start Backend Application\n\nExample using Gunicorn:\n\n```bash\ngunicorn -w 4 -b 0.0.0.0:9898 app:app\n```\n\n---\n\n# 12. Build Frontend\n\n```bash\nnpm install\nnpm run build\n```\n\nThis generates static frontend files.\n\n---\n\n# 13. Configure Nginx\n\nExample configuration:\n\n```nginx\nserver {\n    listen 80;\n    server_name yourdomain.com;\n\n    root /home/ubuntu/apps/project/frontend/dist;\n    index index.html;\n\n    location / {\n        try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html;\n    }\n\n    location /api {\n        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:9898;\n\n        proxy_set_header Host $host;\n        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nRestart Nginx:\n\n```bash\nsudo systemctl restart nginx\n```\n\n---\n\n# 14. Configure systemd Service\n\nExample:\n\n```ini\n[Unit]\nDescription=Application Service\nAfter=network.target\n\n[Service]\nUser=ubuntu\nWorkingDirectory=/home/ubuntu/apps/project/backend\nEnvironmentFile=/home/ubuntu/apps/project/backend/.env\nExecStart=/home/ubuntu/apps/project/backend/venv/bin/gunicorn \\\n    -w 4 \\\n    -b 127.0.0.1:9898 \\\n    app:app\n\nRestart=always\n\n[Install]\nWantedBy=multi-user.target\n```\n\nEnable service:\n\n```bash\nsudo systemctl daemon-reload\nsudo systemctl enable app\nsudo systemctl start app\n```\n\n---\n\n# 15. Configure Domain\n\nUse any domain provider.\n\nRecommended:\n\n* Cloudflare Registrar\n* Porkbun\n* Namecheap\n\nPoint the domain DNS A record to the Elastic IP.\n\n---\n\n# 16. Enable HTTPS\n\nOption 1:\n\n* Use Cloudflare proxy and SSL\n\nOption 2:\n\nInstall Certbot:\n\n```bash\nsudo apt install certbot python3-certbot-nginx\n```\n\nGenerate certificates:\n\n```bash\nsudo certbot --nginx\n```\n\n---\n\n# 17. Useful Commands\n\n## Restart backend service\n\n```bash\nsudo systemctl restart app\n```\n\n## Restart Nginx\n\n```bash\nsudo systemctl restart nginx\n```\n\n## Check logs\n\n```bash\njournalctl -u app -f\n```\n\n## Check Redis\n\n```bash\nsudo systemctl status redis-server\n```\n\n---\n\n# Recommended Production Practices\n\n* Use Nginx as reverse proxy\n* Use Gunicorn/Uvicorn for Python apps\n* Keep Redis local unless scaling heavily\n* Use Elastic IP for stable networking\n* Use HTTPS everywhere\n* Use virtual environments per project\n* Use separate systemd services per application\n* Avoid exposing internal ports publicly\n* Use SSH keys instead of passwords\n\n---\n\n# Suggested Folder Structure\n\n```text\n/home/ubuntu/apps/\n    ├── app1/\n    ├── app2/\n    ├── datasets/\n    ├── backups/\n    └── logs/\n```\n\n---\n\n# Multi-Application Hosting\n\nA single EC2 instance can host multiple applications.\n\nTypical setup:\n\n```text\nNginx\n    ├── app1.domain.com → localhost:9898\n    ├── app2.domain.com → localhost:9900\n    └── app3.domain.com → localhost:9901\n```\n\n---\n\n# Summary\n\nThis setup provides:\n\n* Full server control\n* Stable production deployment\n* Low recurring cost\n* Support for multiple applications\n* Better performance than many free-tier platforms\n* Scalable architecture for future growth\n";